# case class + explicit companion coexist regardless of declaration order

Regression for `v1-explicit-companion-shadows-case-constructor`: an explicit
`object B` companion must not shadow the case-class constructor, and a case class
declared after its companion must not drop the companion's factories. Both
`B(...)` and `B.factory(...)` work from later ordinary functions.

```scalascript
case class B(x: Int)
def mkEarly(): B = B(1)
object B:
  def of(n: Int): B = B(n)
def mkLate(): B = B(2)

object C:
  def twice(n: Int): C = C(n, n)
case class C(a: Int, b: Int)
def mkC(): C = C(3, 4)

println(mkEarly().x)
println(B.of(5).x)
println(mkLate().x)
println(C.twice(7).a)
println(mkC().a + mkC().b)
```
